Probability Distributions: Binomial and Normal

Binomial Distribution

The binomial distribution describes the number of successes in n independent trials, each with probability p.

Example 1: Fair Coin Flips

Let’s visualize tossing a fair coin 10 times (p = 0.5):

n <- 10
p <- 0.5
x <- 0:n

# Calculate probabilities
probs <- dbinom(x, size = n, prob = p)

# Create data frame
data <- data.frame(x = x, probability = probs)

# Plot
ggplot(data, aes(x = x, y = probability)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue", width = 0.7) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(probability, 3)), vjust = -0.5, size = 3) +
  labs(title = "Binomial Distribution: n=10, p=0.5",
       x = "Number of Heads",
       y = "Probability") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 0:n)

Expected value: E[X] = np

Variance: Var(X) = np(1-p)

Example 2: Comparing Different Probabilities

n <- 20
p_values <- c(0.3, 0.5, 0.7)
x <- 0:n

# Create plots for different p values
plots <- lapply(p_values, function(p) {
  probs <- dbinom(x, size = n, prob = p)
  data <- data.frame(x = x, probability = probs)
  
  ggplot(data, aes(x = x, y = probability)) +
    geom_col(fill = "steelblue", width = 0.7) +
    labs(title = paste("n =", n, ", p =", p),
         x = "Number of Successes",
         y = "Probability") +
    theme_minimal() +
    ylim(0, 0.25)
})

grid.arrange(grobs = plots, ncol = 3)

Example 3: Effect of Sample Size

Notice how the distribution becomes more symmetric as n increases:

p <- 0.3
n_values <- c(10, 30, 50)

plots <- lapply(n_values, function(n) {
  x <- 0:n
  probs <- dbinom(x, size = n, prob = p)
  data <- data.frame(x = x, probability = probs)
  
  ggplot(data, aes(x = x, y = probability)) +
    geom_col(fill = "coral", width = 0.7) +
    labs(title = paste("n =", n, ", p =", p),
         x = "Number of Successes",
         y = "Probability") +
    theme_minimal()
})

grid.arrange(grobs = plots, ncol = 3)

Normal Distribution

The normal distribution is a continuous probability distribution characterized by its bell shape.

Standard Normal Distribution

x <- seq(-4, 4, length.out = 1000)
y <- dnorm(x, mean = 0, sd = 1)

data <- data.frame(x = x, density = y)

ggplot(data, aes(x = x, y = density)) +
  geom_line(color = "darkblue", size = 1) +
  geom_area(fill = "lightblue", alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(x = "x",
       y = "Probability Density") +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  annotate("text", x = 0, y = 0.42, label = "mean = 0", color = "red")

The 68-95-99.7 Rule

x <- seq(-4, 4, length.out = 1000)
y <- dnorm(x)

# Create base plot
p <- ggplot(data.frame(x = x, y = y), aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "The 68-95-99.7 Rule",
       x = "Standard Deviations from Mean",
       y = "Density")

# Add shaded regions
p <- p +
  geom_area(data = subset(data.frame(x = x, y = y), x >= -1 & x <= 1),
            aes(x = x, y = y), fill = "darkgreen", alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_area(data = subset(data.frame(x = x, y = y), x >= -2 & x <= 2),
            aes(x = x, y = y), fill = "green", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_area(data = subset(data.frame(x = x, y = y), x >= -3 & x <= 3),
            aes(x = x, y = y), fill = "lightgreen", alpha = 0.3)

# Add annotations
p <- p +
  annotate("text", x = 0, y = 0.2, label = "68%", size = 6, fontface = "bold") +
  annotate("text", x = 0, y = 0.1, label = "95%", size = 5) +
  annotate("text", x = 0, y = 0.05, label = "99.7%", size = 4) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3), 
             linetype = "dashed", alpha = 0.5)

print(p)

Comparing Different Normal Distributions

x <- seq(-10, 20, length.out = 1000)

distributions <- data.frame(
  x = rep(x, 3),
  density = c(dnorm(x, mean = 0, sd = 1),
              dnorm(x, mean = 3, sd = 1),
              dnorm(x, mean = 10, sd = 1.5)),
  distribution = rep(c("N(0, 1)", "N(3, 1)", "N(10, 2.25)"), 
                     each = length(x))
)

ggplot(distributions, aes(x = x, y = density, color = distribution)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  labs(title = "Comparing Normal Distributions",
       x = "x",
       y = "Probability Density",
       color = "Distribution") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1")

Binomial Approximation to Normal

When n is large, the binomial distribution can be approximated by a normal distribution with μ = np and σ² = np(1-p).

n <- 50
p <- 0.5
x <- 0:n

# Binomial probabilities
binomial_probs <- dbinom(x, size = n, prob = p)

# Normal approximation
mean_norm <- n * p
sd_norm <- sqrt(n * p * (1 - p))
normal_density <- dnorm(x, mean = mean_norm, sd = sd_norm)

# Create comparison plot
data <- data.frame(
  x = x,
  Binomial = binomial_probs,
  Normal = normal_density
)

ggplot(data, aes(x = x)) +
  geom_col(aes(y = Binomial), fill = "steelblue", alpha = 0.6, width = 0.8) +
  geom_line(aes(y = Normal), color = "red", size = 1.5) +
  labs(title = paste("Binomial(n=", n, ", p=", p, ") vs Normal Approximation"),
       x = "Number of Successes",
       y = "Probability / Density") +
  theme_minimal() +
  annotate("text", x = 35, y = max(binomial_probs) * 0.9, 
           label = "Blue bars: Binomial\nRed line: Normal", 
           color = "black", hjust = 0)
